# Revision history for PAGI-Tools

0.002000
  - PAGI::Headers - new ordered, case-insensitive, multi-value header
    container. Values are opaque bytes passed through untouched (CR/LF/NUL
    included; wire safety is the server's emission job per the spec) but MUST
    be defined: add/set/set_default croak on an undef value rather than store a
    [name, undef] footgun. to_hash returns { Name => last-value } and to_hash(1)
    returns { Name => [all values] } (values are not comma-joined, unlike
    HTTP::Headers/Mojo::Headers). PAGI::Response now stores and renders its
    headers through PAGI::Headers - new remove_header, content_type clearing,
    ASCII-folded header names, and a writer() that emits a real header arrayref
    with one authoritative Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding stripped.
    PAGI::Request->headers() returns a PAGI::Headers clone snapshot.
  - is_sent now reflects the connection, not the scope. PAGI::Response and
    PAGI::Context report is_sent from the response-started fact on the
    pagi.connection object instead of a scope scalar, so it survives the shallow
    scope copy middleware makes (a cloned scope no longer loses the flag).
    writer()'s single-takeover guard is restored as a per-response instance
    flag, independent of that fact. New PAGI::Test::ConnectionState models the
    full pagi.connection double (disconnect + response_started); PAGI::Test::Client
    seeds it and drives response_started from the send stream.
  - PAGI::Response charset now follows the body. text/html/send append
    "; charset=utf-8" to a charset-less Content-Type (RFC 7303); json() emits
    a bare "application/json" (RFC 8259 defines no charset for JSON). An explicit
    charset set by the caller is never overridden.
  - PAGI::Context conveniences: $ctx->text/html/json/redirect response shorthands
    on Context::HTTP; assert_http/assert_websocket/assert_sse type guards;
    on_default catch-all on the event dispatcher (and run() now throws
    synchronously on re-entry); and raw_send, a stable accessor for the
    underlying $send on any context type (Context::SSE overrides ->send with the
    sse.send convenience, so raw_send is the override-proof channel).
  - Backpressure and lifecycle helpers: on_complete (mirrors on_disconnect) on
    PAGI::Request and PAGI::Context; buffered_amount / high_water_mark /
    low_water_mark accessors; on_high_water / on_drain / is_writable controls;
    and PAGI::WebSocket->deny() for the denial-response extension.
  - PAGI::App::Router coderef route middleware can transform the channel. A
    coderef that calls $next->($scope, $receive, $send) now forwards the
    transformed channel (parity with object middleware); the arg-less $next->()
    continues with the inherited channel. Previously a coderef's transformed
    channel was silently ignored.
  - PAGI::Lifespan reports shutdown-handler failures instead of swallowing them.
  - The canonical scope-adding middleware (Cookie, ContentNegotiation, FormBody,
    JSONBody, MethodOverride, Rewrite, Session) route their scope additions
    through the modify_scope helper (behavior-preserving), whose POD now explains
    the downward-only shallow-copy model.
  - Docs: this distribution's recipes are now PAGI::Tools::Cookbook (the bare
    PAGI::Cookbook name belongs to the protocol cookbook in the PAGI dist); the
    Tutorial and Cookbook examples are corrected against the current API; and
    the chat-showcase example routes via PAGI::App::Router + PAGI::Lifespan.
  - PAGI::Response->has_body_source - public predicate reporting whether a body
    source (buffered body, file, or stream callback) has been registered. A
    build-phase intent signal (true for a registered-but-unrun stream and for
    intentional empty bodies; independent of is_sent). Lets framework authors
    detect "did the handler produce a response?" without reaching into the
    private _body/_file/_stream slots. Documented in PAGI::Response and the new
    PAGI::Tools::Cookbook "Response State & Lifecycle" section.
  - The PAGI application toolkit (PAGI::Middleware::*, PAGI::App::*,
    PAGI::Endpoint::*, PAGI::Request/Response/Context, PAGI::Test::*)
    split out of the PAGI distribution into its own distribution. Git
    history preserved from the original repository
    (https://github.com/jjn1056/pagi).
  - New PAGI::Tools module anchors the distribution.
  - The application runner ships in the PAGI-Server distribution as
    PAGI::Server::Runner (the launcher lives with the server it launches).
  - PAGI::Utils::to_app coerces coderefs, component objects, and class
    names into PAGI apps. All composition points (builder mounts and
    final value, router mount/route targets, Cascade, URLMap,
    PAGI::Test::Client) accept anything it accepts - no more ->to_app
    ceremony at composition sites.
  - builder's enable() accepts configured middleware instances,
    duck-typed on wrap(), matching router route middleware.
  - Spec compliance: PAGI::App::URLMap now sets root_path (was the
    off-spec script_name); PAGI::App::WrapCGI builds SCRIPT_NAME from
    root_path (was reading the never-set script_name).
  - PAGI::Response is now a value. Factories (PAGI::Response->json/text/
    html/redirect/empty) build detached responses with no connection; the
    body methods (text/html/json/send/send_raw/empty/redirect/send_file/
    stream) set the body and return $self; respond($send) is the single
    send primitive; to_app makes any response mountable. PAGI::Context::HTTP
    vends a detached accumulator via response(), and $ctx->respond($res) is
    the guarded send (owns the per-request sent flag). Endpoint HTTP handlers
    now RETURN a respond-able value (returning nothing is a loud error), and
    PAGI::Endpoint::HTTP builds one instance for the app lifetime (keep
    request state on $ctx, not $self). writer() now takes $send as its first
    argument. B<BREAKING>: await $res->json(...) no longer sends -- use
    return $res->json(...) in handlers, or
    await $res->json(...)->respond($send) in raw apps.
  - PAGI::Lifespan->wrap/new coerce their app argument via PAGI::Utils::to_app
    (the sixth and final composition site).
  - PAGI::App::Redirect and PAGI::App::NotFound now build a PAGI::Response value
    internally; their docs lead with the value form (PAGI::Response->redirect
    for a fixed target; PAGI::Response->text(...)->status(404) for a fixed 404)
    and keep the modules for the dynamic case (coderef target/body, query
    preservation). PAGI::App::Healthcheck is unchanged (it is per-request).
  - Documented the PAGI::Response subclassing seam for framework authors:
    construct via new($scope), override respond($send) (the connection is the
    argument, never stored), and build on the public accessor surface rather
    than private internals. Pinned with a subclass test.
  - The Tutorial, Cookbook, PAGI::Response SYNOPSIS/EXAMPLES, and the remaining
    examples are rewritten for the value contract (return a response value /
    respond($send); factories with status/headers options; the value-as-app
    and null-object patterns).
  - PAGI::Request loses its process-global config (the %CONFIG hash and the
    configure/config class methods). Of the eight keys, only path_param_strict
    was ever read at runtime; it is now a per-call option,
    $req->path_params(strict => 1), mirroring path_param's strict option. The
    multipart limits (max_file_size, spool_threshold, etc.) are passed per-call
    to form_params (now documented) and default to the package variables in
    PAGI::Request::MultiPartHandler (local-ize to change a default
    process-wide); max_body_size is the server's concern and is gone from
    Request. B<BREAKING>: PAGI::Request->configure and ->config are removed.
  - PAGI::Endpoint::Router route (method) middleware are now value-flow:
    await $next->() returns the handler's PAGI::Response, which a middleware
    may decorate, observe, short-circuit, or replace, then return (a forgotten
    return is a loud error). The response bubbles up the route's method chain
    and is sent once at the top, rather than at the bottom. Standard event
    middleware remain the outer base, applied at the App::Router mount/group
    level. PAGI::App::Router dispatch now returns the matched HTTP route's
    value (the mechanism enabling the above). PAGI::Endpoint::HTTP is unchanged.
  - PAGI::Request->multipart_stream - pull-based streaming multipart parsing;
    the application controls each part's sink (next/value/stream_to/
    stream_to_file), bypassing the temp-file spool of form_params/uploads.
    Enforces per-field/per-file/per-count and aggregate body limits as bytes
    arrive, writes uploads to new files path-safely (O_EXCL/O_NOFOLLOW, partial
    files unlinked on error), and distinguishes a truncated upload from a clean
    end of stream. Mutually exclusive with the buffered body methods.
  - For changes prior to 0.002000, see the Changes file of the PAGI
    distribution (versions up to 0.001023).
